        "$:/language/Help/server": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/server",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki",
            "text": "The server built in to TiddlyWiki5 is very simple. Although compatible with TiddlyWeb it doesn't support many of the features needed for robust Internet-facing usage.\n\nAt the root, it serves a rendering of a specified tiddler. Away from the root, it serves individual tiddlers encoded in JSON, and supports the basic HTTP operations for `GET`, `PUT` and `DELETE`.\n\n```\n--server <port> <roottiddler> <rendertype> <servetype> <username> <password> <host> <pathprefix>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''port'' - port number to serve from (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''roottiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\") \n* ''rendertype'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''servetype'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''username'' - the default username for signing edits\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''pathprefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n\nIf the password parameter is specified then the browser will prompt the user for the username and password. Note that the password is transmitted in plain text so this implementation isn't suitable for general use.\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n\nThe username and password can be specified as empty strings if you need to set the hostname or pathprefix and don't want to require a password:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html \"\" \"\" 192.168.0.245\n```\n\nTo run multiple TiddlyWiki servers at the same time you'll need to put each one on a different port.\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/setfield": {

            "text": "/*\\\ntitle: $:/core/modules/filters.js\ntype: application/javascript\nmodule-type: wikimethod\n\nAdds tiddler filtering methods to the $tw.Wiki object.\n\n\\*/\n(function(){\n\n/*jslint node: true, browser: true */\n/*global $tw: false */\n\"use strict\";\n\n/*\nParses an operation within a filter string\n\tresults: Array of array of operator nodes into which results should be inserted\n\tfilterString: filter string\n\tp: start position within the string\nReturns the new start position, after the parsed operation\n*/\nfunction parseFilterOperation(operators,filterString,p) {\n\tvar operator, operand, bracketPos, curlyBracketPos;\n\t// Skip the starting square bracket\n\tif(filterString.charAt(p++) !== \"[\") {\n\t\tthrow \"Missing [ in filter expression\";\n\t}\n\t// Process each operator in turn\n\tdo {\n\t\toperator = {};\n\t\t// Check for an operator prefix\n\t\tif(filterString.charAt(p) === \"!\") {\n\t\t\toperator.prefix = filterString.charAt(p++);\n\t\t}\n\t\t// Get the operator name\n\t\tvar nextBracketPos = filterString.substring(p).search(/[\\[\\{<\\/]/);\n\t\tif(nextBracketPos === -1) filterString.substring(p,nextBracketPos);\n\t\t\n\t\t// Any suffix?\n\t\tvar colon = operator.operator.indexOf(':');\n\t\tif(colon > -1) {\n\t\t\toperator.suffix = operator.operator.substring(colon + !MNIST with plain old neural nets
*  I trained MNIST with plain old neural nets, trying to reach 1.6% of "best practices for convolutional neural networks applied to document analysis of Patrice Y.Smard" which is the  best test error rate I found for MNIST which is using only plain old neural networks without any tricks like data augmentation, fine-tuning, etc

* I could get ~1.7,1.8% test error rate on MNIST with plain old neural networks with 700 hidden units and one hidden layer, I am near the result of "best practices for convolutional neural networks applied to document analysis" where they found 1.6% with 800 hidden units. The strategy was to make sure first that the training error was optimized well, putting a small value on L2 weight decay (0.000001) and trying different values by increasing it until getting 1.7%, the training was done in the LLR GPUs and can take typically 15 minutes</b>








! MNIST with plain old neural nets

* I still did not get 1.6% of  "best practices for convolutional neural networks applied to document analysis" (see [[12th January 2015]] ). I added today cross validation to automatize a little bit searching for the best weight decay and number of hidden units in the hidden layer - I still get a test error rate above 1.6%

!Training ILC calorimeter binarized data to reconstruct themselves with auto-encoders

* I transformed ILC data to binary to simplify the problem (energy > 0 ==> 1, energy=0 ==> 0)
* I first trained it with one hidden layer of 500 units with AdaDelta + sigmoid units, the optimization was difficult, the reconstruction error got stuck at around 600 when I used SaltAndPepper corruption + sparsity on the activations. ... I removed sparsity and corruption then the optimization is far more better now, the reconstruction error went near to 0. I will have to retest it to diagnose wether the problem came from sparsity or corruption
Visualization of some examples and their reconstruction (left : original example, right : reconstruction):
{{auto_encoder_ilc.png}}

!The unfolding trick

I built with pylearn2 : stacked RBMs + unfolding + fine tuning autoencoders to learn codes like in  like in "Reducing the Dimensionality of Data with Neural Networks G. E. Hinton* and R. Salakhutdinov". I ran it for MNIST with the following architecture : 784-400-200-100-50-25

<b>Principal params to tune </b>:

"meta-parameters such as the learning rate, the momentum, the weight-cost, the sparsity target, the initial values of the weights, the number of hidden units and the size of each mini-batch."

in Addition to that:

"There are also
decisions to be made about what types of units to use, whether to update their states stochastically
or deterministically, how many times to update the states of the hidden units for each training case,
and whether to start each sequence of state updates at a data-vector. In addition, it is useful to know
how to monitor the progress of learning and when to terminate the training."

<b>Divide the gradient by the mini-batch size</b>

"To avoid having to change the learning rate when the size of a mini-batch is changed, it is helpful
to divide the total gradient computed on a mini-batch by the size of the mini-batch, so when talking
about learning rates we will assume that they multiply the average, per-case gradient computed on a mini-batch, not the total gradient for the mini-batch."


<b>Number of hidden units</b>
" In discriminative learning, the amount of constraint that a training case
imposes on the parameters is equal to the number of bits that it takes to specify the label. Labels
usually contain very few bits of information, so using more parameters than training cases will typ-
ically cause severe overfitting.", comprend pas







Source : [[http://arxiv.org/pdf/1406.2661.pdf]], [[https://github.com/goodfeli/adversarial]]

!Concept

We see the  training of a generative model as a competition game where we have a discriminator D and a generator G, they play one after the other the following game:

* for D, knowing the generator G and the data distribution (training examples) it tries to change itself so that it classifies well between data coming from the generator and data coming from the data distribution : it tries to change itself to give a high score to data coming from the distribution and a low score to data coming from the generator G.

* For G, knowing the discriminator D and the data distribution it tries to change itself to fool the discriminator D so that the discriminator give higher scores to data coming from the generator. The point is that the only way for the generator G to change itself to fool the discriminator that way is to become similar to the distribution of the data so that the discriminator D doesn't know how to separate between the distribution of G and the distribution of the data.
* This concept is powerful because I think in principle you could use it with any of model for both discriminator and generator, in this way it is very useful as a framework (compared to RBMs etc) because it can be extended very easily.

The cost function is the following : 

{{CodeCogsEqn1.gif}}

D tries to maximize it while G tries to minimize it.

!Theoretical result

* they first proved that the solution of the minimax game (D tries maximize the cost function while G tries to minimize it) is G becoming a generative model of the data distribution and D not able to separate the distribution of the data and the distribution of the generator G giving 0.5 everywhere
* then they proved that the proposed algorithm optimizes the minimax game
* they assumed non-parametric models for D and G

! Algorithm

For each iteration :

* Sample a mini-batch  of m noise examples z (z1, z2,...zm) from noise prior of G
* Sample a mini-batch of m examples x (x1,x2,..xm) from data generating distribution
* Update the discriminator D by gradient descent to maximize the cost function by using the noise examples z , the mini-batch of m examples x from the data distribution and by fixing the generator G
* do the three steps above k times
* sample a mini-batch of m examples from noise examples z (z1, z2, ...zm)
* Update the generator by gradient descent to minimize the cost function by using the noise examples z and by fixing the discriminator D

source : [[http://arxiv.org/pdf/1003.0358.pdf]]

They got 0.35% with <b>plain old</b> neural networks on MNIST. "All we
need to achieve this best result so far are many hidden layers, many neurons per layer,
numerous deformed training images, and graphics cards to greatly speed up learning"








Source : [[https://jmozah.github.io/links/]]






Source : [[http://arxiv.org/pdf/1409.5185v2.pdf]]

In this paper they adress three problems in DL: 

* transparency of the intermediate layers to the overall classification 
* discriminativeness and robustness of learned features"
* effectiveness in training, due to the presence of the exploding and vanishing gradients.

they do so by introducting a '''companion objective'' in addition to the current objective of minimizing the error.

''Results'' :  significant performance gain over existing methods (e.g. all state-of-the-art
results on MNIST, CIFAR-10, CIFAR-100, and SVHN)

There are some problems with DL 

* some portions of layers tend to be opaque ?? (meaning : they are not useful?), especially in the early layers
* training difficulty due to vanishing gradients + exploding gradients.

What do they propose :

* They propose, to deal with these problems a companion objective which is a new regulizer(constraint).
* they get significant state of the art results
* they prove mathematically thay this method improve the convergence rate under the framework of SGD assuming local strong convexity of the loss function

http://hoggresearch.blogspot.co.nz/2015/01/yet-another-generative-model-for-images.html

yet another generative model for images
Work continued today with Frean and Brewer. After a second long day of talk, we came up with a plan, which is a generative model for astronomical images and (limited) implementation goals. The model is that the image has compact patches generated by a "source" model and the rest is generated by a "background" model. Each of these submodels—every source and the background—has a unique generating pixel histogram; no other spatial information in the image is used at all! That is, the model is that there are contiguous patches, within each of which the pixel data are produced by iid draws from a unique histogram model.

The nice thing is that Frean has good "Dirichlet multinomial" technology for marginalizing over histograms under a particular prior, so the model can be marginalized trivially. This project violates many of my rules, because it makes very little use of my knowledge of astronomy, and it employs conjugate priors, which are always wrong. That said, all models are wrong, so sometimes expediency is a good idea. This project is very aligned with others of my rules, because we have been able to write down a full likelihood and priors over all of the nuisance parameters. That is, we have a generative model for astronomical images. It isn't a good model, but it is (or might be) very fast to compute. We also have a graphical-model representation of it all.

We are ready to code, and hope to start tomorrow. One strong intuition we have is that there are very simple index-algebra and precomputation things we can do to make the (marginalized) likelihood values very easy to compute. I hope this ends up being true!

This is the original dropout paper.
Source : [[http://arxiv.org/pdf/1207.0580v1.pdf]]

* dropout = turning an activation of a unit to zero with a probability 0.5 to force it to not rely to the other units to give the good predictions...
* small train data = different ways of optimizing the weights to fit the training data = overfitting because each configuration of weights will give a new predictor
*  Another way to see dropout is model averaging "Random dropout makes it possible to train a huge number of different networks in a reasonable time" as opposed to model averaging...
* <b>In networks with a single hidden layer of N units and a “softmax” output layer for
computing the probabilities of the class labels, using the mean network is exactly equivalent
to taking the geometric mean of the probability distributions over labels predicted by all 2^N
possible networks</b> HOW?
* For MNIST, they did not use model averaging, convolutions, pre-training just dropout
* Without using any of these tricks, the best published result for a standard feedforward neural network is 160 errors on the test set." , 160 errors = 0.016 = 1.6% : <b>PAS DE SOURCE</b>
*

* Hidden markov models are sequence learners too but they are discrete (the states?) and cannot store real values 
* Gradent-based RNNs  search in the algorithmic space :  <b>select the best possible program to solve a certain task ?</b>

what is good with openbsd ?

* they compile their software on actual hardware not on virtual machines
* they seem to be very rigourous, more than linux/linux distribs ?
* it has good documentation: "The quality of OpenBSD documentation is on a level I didn't expect even after reading about it in so many places. Not only will you get information on how something works, what's possible and how to use it. It will also tell you the best practices for using the tool and warn you about the common pitfalls."
*  people run openbsd on their actual hardware not on virtual machines, if something fails, you have a userbase who can fix it
* "f OpenBSD states that something is configured then it works and will remain working flawlessly or will only get better over time."

* OpenBSD mailing lists : useful
* you got the source of all programs into your hdd, you feel connected with your OS

* install zero-mq : `wget http://download.zeromq.org/zeromq-4.1.0-rc1.tar.gz, ./configure --prefix=$HOME/local`
* `git clone https://github.com/facebook/iTorch.git;cd iTorch`
* luarocks install lzmq ZMQ_DIR=$HOME/local
* luarocks make
* use it "itorch" :)
